I'm sorry @RyanCavanaugh, I'm having trouble comprehending your example. In my eyes, it further demonstrates that the issue I described exists, i.e. `assertion(0, withArgs)` is illegal. I understand that resolving `In` and `Out` is undecidable (because it recurses infinitely), however, my claim here is that at least the tuple/overload assignment _should be legal_, because both functions may be called only with an equivalent set of arguments. In other words:
```ts
// this is ok:
assertion(0, assertion);
// this is also ok:
withArgs(0, withArgs);
// and this SHOULD be okay, but isn't:
withArgs(0, assertion);
// the other way SHOULD also be okay (your example):
assertion(0, withArgs)
```

